# Clerk Authentication

All authentication is handled by [Clerk](https://clerk.com). Do not add other auth providers or custom session/token logic.

## Key files

- Middleware: [proxy.ts](mdc:proxy.ts) — `clerkMiddleware()` protects routes
- Provider: [app/layout.tsx](mdc:app/layout.tsx) — `ClerkProvider`, sign-in/up UI
- Sign-in/up pages: [app/sign-in/[[...sign-in]]/page.tsx](mdc:app/sign-in/[[...sign-in]]/page.tsx), [app/sign-up/[[...sign-up]]/page.tsx](mdc:app/sign-up/[[...sign-up]]/page.tsx)

## Server-side identity

Get the authenticated user only on the server. Never trust client-supplied user IDs.

```typescript
import { auth, currentUser } from "@clerk/nextjs/server";

// Prefer auth() for userId checks in actions, routes, and data access
const { userId } = await auth();
if (!userId) throw new Error("Unauthorized");

// Use currentUser() when you need profile fields (name, email, etc.)
const user = await currentUser();
if (!user) redirect("/sign-in");
```

- Use `auth()` in Server Actions, Route Handlers, and any code that reads or writes user data
- Use `currentUser()` in Server Components when rendering user-specific UI
- Client components: use Clerk hooks (`useAuth`, `useUser`) for UI state only — never for authorization decisions

## User data isolation

Users must only access their own data. Every read, create, update, and delete must be scoped to the authenticated Clerk `userId`.

- Derive `userId` from `auth()` or `currentUser().id`, never from request body, query params, headers, or client props
- On insert, set `userId` from the authenticated user — never from client input
- On read/update/delete, filter by `userId` so another user's records cannot be returned or modified
- For nested resources (e.g. cards under decks), verify ownership through the parent resource's `userId` before access

See [drizzle-database.mdc](mdc:.cursor/rules/drizzle-database.mdc) for database query examples.

## Do not

- Accept or trust a client-supplied `userId` for authorization
- Query user-owned data without filtering on the authenticated `userId`
- Skip auth checks in Server Actions or Route Handlers because the page "looks" signed-in
- Add alternate auth systems (NextAuth, custom JWT, session cookies)
- Expose one user's decks, cards, or profile data to another user
